In some cases, ancient burial mounds such as the {{ill|Ryūkakuji Iwaya Kofun|ja|龍角寺岩屋古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Chiba Prefecture|ja|千葉県|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Inba District|ja|印旛郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Sakae Town|ja|栄町|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (see also <ref>{{Sfn|神野|2009|p=16}}</ref>), or the {{ill|Kankanmuro Yokonaketsu Group|ja|カンカンムロ横穴群|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in {{ill|Shisui Town|ja|酒々井町|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, have become legendary sites for such tales, where horizontal stone chambers ({{ill|Subterranean Stone Chamber (Horizontal)|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) or horizontal cave tombs ({{ill|Horizontal Cave Tomb|ja|横穴墓|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) are featured. In the case of Shisui Town (Kankanmuro), although the initially prayed-to entity for borrowing bowls was {{ill|Benzaiten|ja|弁財天|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the being actually present within the horizontal cave tomb that lends the trays and bowls remains unidentified.
Some houses or regions retain bowls that were supposedly not returned by the ungrateful, or documents attesting to a default in repayment. Among these items, some hint at a connection with the {{ill|Mochishi|ja|木地師|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, leading to the interpretation that the legends originated from recitations ({{ill|Verbal Formula|ja|口上|qq=draft|qq=draft}}) heard during trade with these craftsmen.<ref>『神話伝説辞典』, 東京堂出版, 1968, 第6刷, pp.471–472</ref> In regions where meal trays and bowls are considered communal property of the village, the tales are also viewed as cautionary narratives that admonish against stealing or breaking borrowed items.<ref>柳田國男『定本 柳田國男集 第五巻』, 筑摩書房, 1977, 第14刷, pp.238–239</ref>
== On the “Silent Trade” Theory == There is controversy among folklorists regarding the theory that the Lending Bowl Legend represents a form of {{ill|Silent Trade|ja|沈黙交易|lt=Silent Trade|lt_ja=無言貿易|qq=draft|qq=draft}} with foreigners. In 1917 (the 6th year of the Taishō period), the anthropologist {{ill|Ryūzō Torii|ja|鳥居龍蔵|qq=draft|qq=draft}} pointed out in the ''Anthropological Journal'' that the Lending Bowl Legend is a “silent trade” – that is, a trade conducted without the parties coming into contact or exchanging words (i.e., a translated term for “Silent trade”). In response, in 1918 (Taishō 7), {{ill|Kunio Yanagida|ja|柳田国男|qq=draft|qq=draft}} published an article titled “Hidden Village” in the ''Tokyo Nichinichi Shimbun'', arguing that the Lending Bowl Legend is merely a lending-borrowing relationship and, furthermore, that since the counterpart is a {{ill|Deity|ja|神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it is a phenomenon of faith—a form of expression of the “otherworldly concept” similar to the Dragon Palace Legend and hidden village legends.
After the war, in 1954 (Showa 29), {{ill|Toshio Kitami|ja|北見俊夫|qq=draft|qq=draft}} compiled cases of the Lending Bowl Legend from across Japan and denied that it constituted a “silent trade”. On the other hand, in 1979, {{ill|Shinichirō Kurimoto|ja|栗本慎一郎|qq=draft|qq=draft}} argued in ''Economic Anthropology'' that the Lending Bowl Legend is indeed a “silent trade”, representing a primitive form of commerce.
Regarding the view that “silent trade” is the “primordial form of trade”, in the same year {{ill|Masao Oka|ja|岡正雄|qq=draft|qq=draft}} argued in ''Ijin Sonota'' that “silent trade” is not a primitive form of trade but merely a special type of exchange—a custom of friendly gift-giving predicated on the hospitality extended to guests.
== Worldwide Lending Bowl Legends == In {{ill|France|ja|フランス|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, there is a story in which one beseeches a mound to lend a {{ill|Pot|ja|鍋|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.
