== Overview ==
In Japan prior to the early modern period, families did not possess more tableware than was necessary for the household; consequently, during events that gathered large numbers of people, such as weddings, it was not uncommon for meal trays and bowls to be borrowed from elsewhere.

The Lending Bowl Legend has spread over a wide area of Japan—from {{ill|Okuwa|ja|奥羽|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Okuwa|qq=}} to [[:en:Kyushu|Kyushu]]—but is especially prevalent in the mountainous regions of the [[:en:Chūbu region|Chūbu region]] and {{ill|Northern Kanto|ja|北関東|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Northern Kanto|qq=}}. Although the basic storyline is generally the same as in the example above, there are many minor variations. The lending party may be various beings such as {{ill|Child Deity|ja|童子|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Child Deity|qq=}}, [[:en:Kappa (folklore)|Kappa]], {{ill|Dragon|ja|龍|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Dragon|qq=}}, [[:en:Kami|Goddess]], {{ill|Jizō Bosatsu|ja|お地蔵様|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Jizō Bosatsu|qq=}}, or other mysterious or diverse entities.

The lending locations vary as well; they may be directly visited at abysses ([[:en:Stream pool|Abyss]]), waterfalls ([[:en:Waterfall|Waterfall]]), rocks, or caves ({{ill|Cave|ja|洞穴|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Cave|qq=}}) in the shady parts of mountains, or even in hidden villages ([[:en:Hidden village|Hidden Village]]). Comparatively, many of these locations are associated with water, and there are numerous legends that appear to be related to the worship of the {{ill|Water God Shōdōtan|ja|水神少童譚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Water God Shōdōtan|qq=}} and the [[:en:Suijin|water god]]. In some tales, a relationship is already established through which one may borrow meal trays and bowls, while in others the bowls are seen to flow from upstream in a river, leading to the discovery of an otherworld or hidden village.

In some cases, ancient burial mounds such as the {{ill|Ryūkakuji Iwaya Kofun|ja|龍角寺岩屋古墳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ryūkakuji Iwaya Kofun|qq=}} in [[:en:Chiba Prefecture|Chiba Prefecture]], [[:en:Inba District|Inba District]], [[:en:Sakae, Chiba|Sakae Town]] (see also <ref>{{Sfn|神野|2009|p=16}}</ref>), or the {{ill|Kankanmuro Yokonaketsu Group|ja|カンカンムロ横穴群|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kankanmuro Yokonaketsu Group|qq=}} in [[:en:Shisui|Shisui Town]], have become legendary sites for such tales, where horizontal stone chambers ({{ill|Subterranean Stone Chamber (Horizontal)|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|2=ja|3=横穴式石室|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|4=zh|5=橫穴式石室|6=ko|7=굴식 돌방무덤|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Subterranean Stone Chamber (Horizontal)|13=User:Immanuelle/Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|qq=}}) or horizontal cave tombs ({{ill|Horizontal Cave Tomb|ja|横穴墓|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Horizontal Cave Tomb|qq=}}) are featured. In the case of Shisui Town (Kankanmuro), although the initially prayed-to entity for borrowing bowls was {{ill|Benzaiten|ja|弁財天|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Benzaiten|qq=}}, the being actually present within the horizontal cave tomb that lends the trays and bowls remains unidentified.

Some houses or regions retain bowls that were supposedly not returned by the ungrateful, or documents attesting to a default in repayment. Among these items, some hint at a connection with the [[:en:Kijiya|Mochishi]], leading to the interpretation that the legends originated from recitations ({{ill|Verbal Formula|ja|口上|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Verbal Formula|qq=}}) heard during trade with these craftsmen.<ref>『神話伝説辞典』, 東京堂出版, 1968, 第6刷, pp.471–472</ref> In regions where meal trays and bowls are considered communal property of the village, the tales are also viewed as cautionary narratives that admonish against stealing or breaking borrowed items.<ref>柳田國男『定本 柳田國男集 第五巻』, 筑摩書房, 1977, 第14刷, pp.238–239</ref>

== On the “Silent Trade” Theory ==
There is controversy among folklorists regarding the theory that the Lending Bowl Legend represents a form of [[:en:Silent trade|Silent Trade]] with foreigners. In 1917 (the 6th year of the Taishō period), the anthropologist [[:en:Torii Ryūzō|Ryūzō Torii]] pointed out in the ''Anthropological Journal'' that the Lending Bowl Legend is a “silent trade” – that is, a trade conducted without the parties coming into contact or exchanging words (i.e., a translated term for “Silent trade”). In response, in 1918 (Taishō 7), {{ill|Kunio Yanagida|ja|柳田国男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunio Yanagida|qq=}} published an article titled “Hidden Village” in the ''Tokyo Nichinichi Shimbun'', arguing that the Lending Bowl Legend is merely a lending-borrowing relationship and, furthermore, that since the counterpart is a [[:en:Deity|Deity]], it is a phenomenon of faith—a form of expression of the “otherworldly concept” similar to the Dragon Palace Legend and hidden village legends.

After the war, in 1954 (Showa 29), {{ill|Toshio Kitami|ja|北見俊夫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toshio Kitami|qq=}} compiled cases of the Lending Bowl Legend from across Japan and denied that it constituted a “silent trade”. On the other hand, in 1979, [[:en:Shinichiro Kurimoto|Shinichirō Kurimoto]] argued in ''Economic Anthropology'' that the Lending Bowl Legend is indeed a “silent trade”, representing a primitive form of commerce.

Regarding the view that “silent trade” is the “primordial form of trade”, in the same year [[:en:Masao Oka|Masao Oka]] argued in ''Ijin Sonota'' that “silent trade” is not a primitive form of trade but merely a special type of exchange—a custom of friendly gift-giving predicated on the hospitality extended to guests.

== Worldwide Lending Bowl Legends ==
In [[:en:France|France]], there is a story in which one beseeches a mound to lend a [[:en:Stock pot|Pot]].

