== On the “Silent Trade” Theory == There is controversy among folklorists regarding the theory that the Lending Bowl Legend represents a form of [[:en:Silent trade|Silent Trade]] with foreigners. In 1917 (the 6th year of the Taishō period), the anthropologist [[:en:Torii Ryūzō|Ryūzō Torii]] pointed out in the ''Anthropological Journal'' that the Lending Bowl Legend is a “silent trade” – that is, a trade conducted without the parties coming into contact or exchanging words (i.e., a translated term for “Silent trade”). In response, in 1918 (Taishō 7), {{ill|Kunio Yanagida|ja|柳田国男|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kunio Yanagida|qq=}} published an article titled “Hidden Village” in the ''Tokyo Nichinichi Shimbun'', arguing that the Lending Bowl Legend is merely a lending-borrowing relationship and, furthermore, that since the counterpart is a [[:en:Deity|Deity]], it is a phenomenon of faith—a form of expression of the “otherworldly concept” similar to the Dragon Palace Legend and hidden village legends.
After the war, in 1954 (Showa 29), {{ill|Toshio Kitami|ja|北見俊夫|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toshio Kitami|qq=}} compiled cases of the Lending Bowl Legend from across Japan and denied that it constituted a “silent trade”. On the other hand, in 1979, [[:en:Shinichiro Kurimoto|Shinichirō Kurimoto]] argued in ''Economic Anthropology'' that the Lending Bowl Legend is indeed a “silent trade”, representing a primitive form of commerce.
Regarding the view that “silent trade” is the “primordial form of trade”, in the same year [[:en:Masao Oka|Masao Oka]] argued in ''Ijin Sonota'' that “silent trade” is not a primitive form of trade but merely a special type of exchange—a custom of friendly gift-giving predicated on the hospitality extended to guests.
== Worldwide Lending Bowl Legends == In [[:en:France|France]], there is a story in which one beseeches a mound to lend a [[:en:Stock pot|Pot]].
