[[File:Wankishi ike cropped Totomi Koseki Zue Frame 22.jpg|thumb|300px|[[:en:Tōtōmi Province|Tōtomi Province]] {{ill|Sano District|ja|佐野郡|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Sano District|qq=|1=Saya district|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11385111}} {{ill|Tomibe Village|ja|富部村|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tomibe Village|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki link invalid}}’s Lending Bowl Legend as depicted in a color painting from the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]] (from the edition of “Wangan Ike” by {{ill|Fujichōkō|ja|藤長庚|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Fujichōkō|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 兵藤庄右衛門|1=Hyōdō Shōemon|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q110647440}} in the {{ill|Tōtomi Ancient Monuments Illustrated Collection|ja|遠江古蹟圖會|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōtomi Ancient Monuments Illustrated Collection|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 兵藤庄右衛門|1=Hyōdō Shōemon|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q110647440}}, 1803; held by the [[:en:National Diet Library|National Diet Library]])]] '''Lending Bowl Legend''' (わんかしでんせつ) is a collective term for a type of folk tale and traditional narrative – one of the narrative types of folklore – whose central theme is a story in which meal trays ({{ill|Meal Tray|ja|膳|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Meal Tray|qq=|1=zen|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11612404}}) or bowls ({{ill|Bowl|ja|椀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Bowl|qq=|1=wan|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11540470}}) are borrowed from mounds, abysses, large rocks, or caves in the shady parts of mountains.<ref>柳田國男『定本 柳田國男集 第五巻』筑摩書房, 1977, 第14刷, p.230</ref>
== Examples of the Lending Bowl Legend == {{Quote|In a place called Kanaya, there was a large rock, and when one shouted beside that rock, “Lend me meal trays and bowls for as many people as I need,” the next morning the desired number of trays and bowls were prepared. One time, when an ungrateful person returned fewer bowls than he had borrowed, he was never lent any again.|[[:en:Tottori Prefecture|Tottori Prefecture]] [[:en:Yazu District, Tottori|Hattō District]]’s tradition|『昔話伝説小事典』, みずうみ書房, 1987, p.273}}
== Overview == In Japan prior to the early modern period, families did not possess more tableware than was necessary for the household; consequently, during events that gathered large numbers of people, such as weddings, it was not uncommon for meal trays and bowls to be borrowed from elsewhere.
